{"parentUuid":"4c70f383-b8c3-47b9-8de5-10aa0e25db0e","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9e3842d3be64b93d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_YDk6B4h42dWqu4JODHd92yyp","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→component: cleanup-audit\n     3→deliverable: D-0026\n     4→source_comparison: comparison-cleanup-audit.md\n     5→verdict: IC stronger\n     6→principle_primary: Evidence Integrity\n     7→principle_secondary: Deterministic Gates\n     8→generated: 2026-03-15\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→# Improvement Plan: Cleanup-Audit CLI\n    12→\n    13→Traceability source: D-0022 merged-strategy.md. All items trace to one or more of the five architectural principles.\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## ITEM CA-001 — Presumption of Falsehood in Audit Agent Instructions\n    18→\n    19→**Priority**: P0\n    20→**Effort**: S\n    21→**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    22→**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's Presumption of Falsehood epistemic stance, not LW's anti-hallucination structured evidence table enforcement for all output types\n    23→**Why not full import**: LW's full implementation requires per-claim structured evidence tables with mandatory FAS -100 penalty scoring; IC's audit system needs only the epistemic stance (start from \"unverified\") applied to agent behavioral instructions, not a new evidence-accounting infrastructure.\n    24→\n    25→**File paths and change description**:\n    26→- `src/superclaude/agents/audit-scanner.md` — Add to the behavioral instructions: \"Default classification status for all file findings is UNVERIFIED until evidence is gathered. Do not assume a file is safe-to-delete or safe-to-keep without positive evidence. If no importers are found for a file, document 'no importers found' explicitly — do not leave absence of evidence undocumented.\"\n    27→- `src/superclaude/agents/audit-validator.md` — Add to validation instructions: \"Treat all scanner findings as unverified claims. Each finding requires positive confirmation before PASS classification. Document when confirmation evidence is absent (not just when it is found).\"\n    28→- `.claude/agents/audit-scanner.md` and `.claude/agents/audit-validator.md` — Sync copies (via `make sync-dev`).\n    29→\n    30→**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 1 (Evidence Integrity), direction 2: \"Audit agents should default classification status to 'unverified' until evidence is gathered, not 'classified' pending flagging.\"\n    31→\n    32→**Dependencies**: None (foundational for CA-002)\n    33→**Acceptance criteria**: audit-scanner.md contains the word \"UNVERIFIED\" as a default classification state in its instructions; audit-validator.md contains explicit instructions to document absence of confirmation; both agent files have matching dev copies.\n    34→**Risk**: Low. Agent instruction additions; no code changes; behavioral improvement only.\n    35→\n    36→---\n    37→\n    38→## ITEM CA-002 — Mandatory Negative Evidence Documentation\n    39→\n    40→**Priority**: P0\n    41→**Effort**: S\n    42→**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    43→**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's mandatory negative evidence documentation requirement (not LW's structured evidence tables or PABLOV chain)\n    44→**Why not full import**: LW implements negative evidence through per-claim tables in all output types at all tiers; IC needs mandatory negative evidence only in audit report outputs (not in all verification outputs at all tiers).\n    45→\n    46→**File paths and change description**:\n    47→- `src/superclaude/cli/audit/scanner_schema.py` — In the Phase 1 schema, add an optional but logged `negative_evidence` field to finding records: when `has_references` is False and no importers are found, the field must be set to `\"no_importers_found\"` or similar value. The schema validator should warn (not error) when this field is absent for a zero-reference finding.\n    48→- `src/superclaude/cli/audit/classification.py` — In `classify_finding()`, when `has_references=False`, set a `negative_evidence_documented` flag on the `ClassificationResult`. This flag is used by the audit report formatter to verify that negative evidence is explicitly recorded.\n    49→- `src/superclaude/cli/cleanup_audit/executor.py` — In the report generation step, assert that all REVIEW/DELETE findings with zero references have `negative_evidence_documented=True`. Log a warning for any finding where this is absent.\n    50→\n    51→**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 1 (Evidence Integrity), direction 3: \"When an agent finds no importers, no errors, or no supporting evidence for a claim, 'not found' must be explicitly documented as a result. Silent omission is not acceptable.\"\n    52→\n    53→**Dependencies**: CA-001 (epistemic stance must be established in agent instructions first)\n    54→**Acceptance criteria**: `classify_finding()` sets `negative_evidence_documented` on zero-reference findings; executor generates a warning when the flag is absent in a REVIEW/DELETE finding; at least one test verifies the flag is set correctly.\n    55→**Risk**: Low. Schema addition is backward-compatible (optional field); warning does not block pipeline.\n    56→\n    57→---\n    58→\n    59→## ITEM CA-003 — Typed State Transitions in Audit Pass Progression\n    60→\n    61→**Priority**: P1\n    62→**Effort**: M\n    63→**Classification**: add new code\n    64→**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's typed inter-agent communication (RESEARCH_READY, TASK_READY, EXECUTION_COMPLETE, BLOCKED) as IC-native typed state transitions for the G-001 → G-002 → G-003 audit pass progression\n    65→**Why not full import**: LW's typed message protocol is implemented via bash inter-process communication; IC's audit passes are Python function-to-function calls. The typed state concept is adoptable; the IPC mechanism is not.\n    66→\n    67→**File paths and change description**:\n    68→- `src/superclaude/cli/cleanup_audit/executor.py` — Define an `AuditPassState` enum with values: `PENDING`, `SCANNING`, `SCAN_COMPLETE`, `ANALYZING`, `ANALYSIS_COMPLETE`, `VALIDATING`, `DONE`, `BLOCKED`. At each pass transition (G-001 → G-002, G-002 → G-003), emit the current state to the audit logger. If a pass returns an empty result set, emit `BLOCKED` with reason.\n    69→- `src/superclaude/cli/pipeline/models.py` — Add `AuditPassState` to the models module export list so consuming code can reference it without importing from executor.\n    70→\n    71→**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 5: \"For IC components that involve sequential agent invocation (cleanup-audit's G-001 → G-002 → G-003 progression), adopt explicit typed state transitions. BLOCKED as a first-class message type prevents silent failures in agent coordination.\"\n    72→\n    73→**Dependencies**: CA-001, CA-002\n    74→**Acceptance criteria**: `AuditPassState` enum exists in executor.py; BLOCKED state is emitted when a pass produces an empty result; each G-001/G-002/G-003 transition logs the current state.\n    75→**Risk**: Medium. New enum and state emission; requires integration test across all three passes.\n    76→\n    77→---\n    78→\n    79→## ITEM CA-004 — Executor Validation Gate Before Agent Invocation\n    80→\n    81→**Priority**: P1\n    82→**Effort**: S\n    83→**Classification**: strengthen existing code\n    84→**patterns_not_mass**: true — adopting LW's executor validation gate pattern (validate input before starting execution) without LW's permissionMode:bypassPermissions or all-opus model requirement\n    85→**Why not full import**: LW's rf-task-executor validation gate is tied to its permissionMode:bypassPermissions agent execution model, which is explicitly rejected in D-0022 Principle 4. The input validation pattern is adoptable; the permission model is not.\n    86→\n    87→**File paths and change description**:\n    88→- `src/superclaude/cli/cleanup_audit/executor.py` — At the beginning of `execute_cleanup_audit()`, before invoking any audit pass, validate: (a) target directory exists and is readable, (b) `--batch-size` is within valid range (1–100), (c) `--focus` value is a known domain (`infrastructure|frontend|backend|all`). If validation fails, emit `AuditPassState.BLOCKED` with reason and return early (fail-fast, not fail-mid-execution).\n    89→- `src/superclaude/cli/cleanup_audit/commands.py` — Move CLI-level validation (Click option types) to complement executor-level validation, not replace it. Executor must re-validate inputs it receives from any call site (not only the CLI).\n    90→\n    91→**Rationale**: D-0022 Principle 5 (Scalable Quality Enforcement), direction 6: \"Before any agent begins execution, it should validate its input file/specification and emit BLOCKED if the structure is invalid.\"\n    92→\n    93→**Dependencies**: CA-003 (BLOCKED state enum must exist)\n    94→**Acceptance criteria**: `execute_cleanup_audit()` validates inputs before the first pass invocation; invalid target path returns BLOCKED immediately; unit test for each validation condition.\n    95→**Risk**: Low. Input validation is additive; no existing code paths are removed.\n    96→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"uuid":"362fbe15-033c-40c6-b6a3-4ef733f7e2d0","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:35.433Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4c70f383-b8c3-47b9-8de5-10aa0e25db0e","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
{"parentUuid":"362fbe15-033c-40c6-b6a3-4ef733f7e2d0","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9e3842d3be64b93d","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"call_LuQbc1FoJK3ccTch7tCp0J0u","toolUseID":"call_LuQbc1FoJK3ccTch7tCp0J0u","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:35.435Z","uuid":"db4fc94f-9c53-4c59-a9a6-f50db18d8955","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
{"parentUuid":"bcece821-aa2e-4fab-9310-7b397a2740fb","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9e3842d3be64b93d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_LuQbc1FoJK3ccTch7tCp0J0u","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Unified Audit Gating System v1.2.1 — Release Specification (Implementation-Ready)\n     2→\n     3→Document status: **Draft for sign-off**\n     4→Decision baseline date: **2026-03-03**\n     5→Primary intent: direct input for roadmap generation and phased tasklist creation.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## 0. Evidence Model and Decision Method\n    10→\n    11→### 0.1 Deterministic findings (normative in this spec)\n    12→Deterministic items are requirements, invariants, contracts, and state/decision rules that are directly specified in source artifacts and are testable/replayable.\n    13→\n    14→### 0.2 Heuristic judgments (advisory in this spec)\n    15→Heuristic items are operational recommendations (e.g., rollout pacing, UX friction mitigation) derived from reviews/risk analysis and are non-authoritative unless promoted to a locked decision.\n    16→\n    17→### 0.3 Citation rule used\n    18→Critical claims cite source file + section label. If section labels are absent, file heading context is used.\n    19→\n    20→---\n    21→\n    22→## 1. Release Scope and Goals\n    23→\n    24→### 1.1 Scope\n    25→Implement a unified audit-gating capability that blocks completion/release transitions unless the corresponding gate passes at three scopes:\n    26→1. Task gate\n    27→2. Milestone gate\n    28→3. Release gate\n    29→\n    30→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Goal; Task-Level Gate; Milestone-Level Gate; Release-Level Gate)\n    31→\n    32→### 1.2 Primary goals\n    33→1. Deterministic pass/fail gating with evidence-backed outputs\n    34→2. Explicit audit workflow states for all scopes\n    35→3. Single primary user interface (`/sc:audit-gate`)\n    36→4. Rollout-safe enforcement (shadow → soft → full)\n    37→\n    38→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Locked Decisions, Non-Functional Requirements, Command & Enforcement; `02-design-spec-v1.md` → Command/API Surface, Migration/Rollout; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → v1.1 Delta Summary)\n    39→\n    40→### 1.3 Out-of-scope for v1.2.1\n    41→- New non-gating product features unrelated to transition control\n    42→- Security hardening expansions not required for correctness of gate transitions\n    43→- Full auto-tuning of profiles during rollout (deferred)\n    44→\n    45→(Constraint source: user hard requirement + `executive-summary.md` → deferred improvements)\n    46→\n    47→---\n    48→\n    49→## 2. Locked Decisions, Non-Goals, and Contradiction Resolution\n    50→\n    51→### 2.1 Locked decisions (authoritative)\n    52→1. Configurable strictness/profile behavior exists\n    53→2. Tier-1 gate is required even for LIGHT/EXEMPT flows\n    54→3. Overrides allowed only for task/milestone (never release)\n    55→4. Single primary command interface\n    56→5. Explicit `audit_*` states are required\n    57→\n    58→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Locked Decisions; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → Locked User Decisions)\n    59→\n    60→### 2.2 Non-goals\n    61→- Release-level override capability\n    62→- LLM/agent heuristics as source of truth for pass/fail\n    63→\n    64→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Locked Decisions/Acceptance Criteria; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → v1.1 Delta Summary A)\n    65→\n    66→### 2.3 Contradictions and winning decisions\n    67→\n    68→| Contradiction | Evidence | Winner in v1.2.1 | Rationale |\n    69→|---|---|---|---|\n    70→| `--strictness standard|strict` vs profile set `strict|standard|legacy_migration` | `02-design-spec-v1.md` → Flags; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → v1.1 Delta Summary B | Canonical model is `--profile strict|standard|legacy_migration`; `--strictness` retained only as temporary alias in shadow/soft, removed at full | Needed for deterministic policy selection and migration compatibility (`design-delta-v1.2.md` → Change 1) |\n    71→| Shorthand state expression can imply terminal transition from failed branch | `02-design-spec-v1.md` → State Machine; `state-machine-validation.md` → Current gap | Explicit legal/illegal transition table is authoritative | Removes ambiguity and enables validator enforcement |\n    72→| “State machine hardening added” vs retry/backoff still open | `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → Delta D + Open Items (3) | v1.2.1 must lock concrete retry/backoff/timeout semantics before GO | Required for deadlock resistance and reproducibility |\n    73→| Rollout phases present but rollback/safe-disable not concrete | `02-design-spec-v1.md` → Migration/Rollout; `05-review-checklist.md` → Section 8 | v1.2.1 defines explicit rollback triggers/contracts | Checklist compliance and operational safety |\n    74→\n    75→---\n    76→\n    77→## 3. Canonical Terminology and Policy Model\n    78→\n    79→### 3.1 Canonical terms\n    80→- **Scope**: `task | milestone | release`\n    81→- **Tier**: `Tier-1(task), Tier-2(milestone), Tier-3(release)`\n    82→- **Profile**: `strict | standard | legacy_migration`\n    83→- **Gate status**: `passed | failed`\n    84→- **Failure class**: `policy | transient | system | timeout | unknown`\n    85→\n    86→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → tier goals; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → profile + schema direction; `design-delta-v1.2.md` → failure-class taxonomy)\n    87→\n    88→### 3.2 Strictness vs profile resolution (normative)\n    89→1. Runtime policy resolver consumes `profile` as canonical input.\n    90→2. If `strictness` is provided, map `strictness=strict|standard` to `profile=strict|standard`.\n    91→3. `legacy_migration` cannot be expressed through `strictness`; must use `profile`.\n    92→4. At full enforcement, `strictness` alias is rejected.\n    93→\n    94→(Source: `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Change 1)\n    95→\n    96→---\n    97→\n    98→## 4. Normative State Machine\n    99→\n   100→### 4.1 Legal transitions\n   101→\n   102→#### Task scope\n   103→- `in_progress -> ready_for_audit_task`\n   104→- `ready_for_audit_task -> audit_task_running`\n   105→- `audit_task_running -> audit_task_passed | audit_task_failed`\n   106→- `audit_task_passed -> completed`\n   107→- `audit_task_failed -> ready_for_audit_task` (retry path)\n   108→- `audit_task_failed -> completed` only with approved task override\n   109→\n   110→#### Milestone scope\n   111→- `in_progress -> ready_for_audit_milestone`\n   112→- `ready_for_audit_milestone -> audit_milestone_running`\n   113→- `audit_milestone_running -> audit_milestone_passed | audit_milestone_failed`\n   114→- `audit_milestone_passed -> completed`\n   115→- `audit_milestone_failed -> ready_for_audit_milestone` (retry path)\n   116→- `audit_milestone_failed -> completed` only with approved milestone override\n   117→\n   118→#### Release scope\n   119→- `in_progress -> ready_for_audit_release`\n   120→- `ready_for_audit_release -> audit_release_running`\n   121→- `audit_release_running -> audit_release_passed | audit_release_failed`\n   122→- `audit_release_passed -> released`\n   123→- `audit_release_failed -> ready_for_audit_release` (retry path)\n   124→- `audit_release_failed -> released` is forbidden\n   125→\n   126→(Source: `state-machine-validation.md` → proposed normative form; `01-requirements-spec.md` → Acceptance Criteria; `02-design-spec-v1.md` → Failure/Override Policy)\n   127→\n   128→### 4.2 Illegal transitions (minimum mandatory set)\n   129→1. `in_progress -> completed/released` (bypass)\n   130→2. `ready_for_audit_* -> completed/released`\n   131→3. `audit_*_running -> completed/released`\n   132→4. `audit_*_failed -> completed` without approved override (task/milestone only)\n   133→5. `audit_release_failed -> released` always\n   134→6. Any transition from terminal state except explicit reopen operation\n   135→\n   136→(Source: `state-machine-validation.md` → Illegal transitions)\n   137→\n   138→### 4.3 Override rules (normative)\n   139→- Task and milestone may override failed gate only with approved `OverrideRecord`\n   140→- Release override is forbidden by invariant\n   141→\n   142→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Locked Decisions/Acceptance Criteria; `02-design-spec-v1.md` → Failure/Override Policy)\n   143→\n   144→### 4.4 Timeout, retry, recovery semantics\n   145→1. `audit_*_running` uses lease + heartbeat.\n   146→2. Missing heartbeat past timeout causes `audit_*_failed(timeout)`.\n   147→3. Retry is bounded by per-scope attempt budget.\n   148→4. Retry exhaustion remains failed and blocks completion/release.\n   149→5. Requeue allowed only while budget remains.\n   150→\n   151→(Source: `state-machine-validation.md` → Stuck-state handling/recovery; `risk-register-v1.2.md` → R2; `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Add 4)\n   152→\n   153→---\n   154→\n   155→## 5. Deterministic Gate Decision Contract\n   156→\n   157→### 5.1 Failure classes\n   158→- `policy`: rule/threshold violation\n   159→- `transient`: recoverable execution issue\n   160→- `system`: non-recoverable runner/system error\n   161→- `timeout`: stale/expired running state\n   162→- `unknown`: unmapped condition (fail-safe)\n   163→\n   164→(Source: `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Add 2; `01-requirements-spec.md` → fail-safe defaults)\n   165→\n   166→### 5.2 Pass/fail rules (normative)\n   167→1. Any blocking check failure => gate `failed`.\n   168→2. Unknown/missing deterministic inputs => `failed`.\n   169→3. Missing evidence for failed check => `failed` and non-completable.\n   170→4. Completion/release transitions require latest gate `passed` except approved task/milestone override path.\n   171→\n   172→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Non-Functional Requirements/Acceptance Criteria; `metrics-and-gates.md` → M5; `state-machine-validation.md`)\n   173→\n   174→### 5.3 Evidence requirements\n   175→Every failed check must include at least one evidence reference:\n   176→- file path OR\n   177→- `file:line`\n   178→\n   179→Drift summary must separate `edited` vs `non-edited`.\n   180→\n   181→(Source: `01-requirements-spec.md` → Reporting + Non-Functional Requirements; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → GateResult schema)\n   182→\n   183→---\n   184→\n   185→## 6. Data Contracts and Versioning\n   186→\n   187→### 6.1 GateResult (normative v1.2.1)\n   188→Required fields:\n   189→- `version`\n   190→- `gate_run_id`\n   191→- `scope`, `entity_id`, `profile`\n   192→- `status`, `score`, `threshold`\n   193→- `checks[]` (includes severity + evidence)\n   194→- `drift_summary` (`edited`, `non_edited`)\n   195→- `override` block\n   196→- `timing` block\n   197→- `artifacts` block\n   198→- `failure_class` (v1.2 addition)\n   199→\n   200→(Source: `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → Canonical GateResult; `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Add 2)\n   201→\n   202→### 6.2 OverrideRecord (normative v1.2.1)\n   203→Required fields:\n   204→- `record_id`, `scope`, `entity_id`\n   205→- `actor`\n   206→- `reason_code`, `reason_text`\n   207→- `created_at`, `expires_at`\n   208→- `linked_gate_run_id`\n   209→- `approver`, `approval_state`, `review_due_at` (v1.2 governance addition)\n   210→\n   211→(Source: `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → Canonical OverrideRecord; `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Change 2)\n   212→\n   213→### 6.3 Transition event schema (normative)\n   214→`GateTransitionEvent` minimum fields:\n   215→- `event_id`, `correlation_id`, `occurred_at`\n   216→- `scope`, `entity_id`\n   217→- `from_state`, `to_state`\n   218→- `cause` (`check_failure|timeout|retry|override|manual_reopen|system_error`)\n   219→- `gate_run_id` (nullable when pre-run)\n   220→\n   221→`GateCheckEvent` minimum fields:\n   222→- `event_id`, `correlation_id`, `gate_run_id`\n   223→- `check_id`, `severity`, `outcome`, `evidence_refs[]`\n   224→\n   225→(Source: `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Add 6; `state-machine-validation.md` → correlation ID replay requirement)\n   226→\n   227→### 6.4 Versioning policy\n   228→- Backward-compatible additions: minor bump\n   229→- Breaking field/semantic changes: major bump\n   230→- Gate evaluator must reject unsupported major versions as `failed(unknown)`\n   231→\n   232→(Source basis: determinism/fail-safe requirements in `01-requirements-spec.md`)\n   233→\n   234→---\n   235→\n   236→## 7. Rollout Contract\n   237→\n   238→### 7.1 Phases\n   239→1. **Shadow**: collect decisions/metrics; no hard business blocking\n   240→2. **Soft**: selective enforcement by profile/scope\n   241→3. **Full**: global enforcement\n   242→\n   243→(Source: `02-design-spec-v1.md` → Migration/Rollout; `04-design-v1.1-delta-handoff.md` → Delta G)\n   244→\n   245→### 7.2 Promotion criteria\n   246→- Shadow -> Soft: pass M1, M4, M5, M7, M9\n   247→- Soft -> Full: pass M1–M12 for two consecutive windows + pass rollback drill (M10)\n   248→\n   249→(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md` → Gate thresholds by rollout phase)\n   250→\n   251→### 7.3 Rollback / safe-disable triggers (normative)\n   252→Immediate rollback to prior phase if any occurs:\n   253→1. M4 determinism breach below threshold\n   254→2. Any M5 evidence completeness failure\n   255→3. Unresolved stale-running incident (M7 fail)\n   256→4. Failed rollback drill in current window (M10 fail)\n   257→5. Transition validator bypass discovered\n   258→\n   259→Rollback order: `full -> soft -> shadow`. Emergency safe-disable keeps shadow artifact production enabled.\n   260→\n   261→(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md`; `risk-register-v1.2.md` R1/R2/R8/R10; `design-delta-v1.2.md` Add 5)\n   262→\n   263→---\n   264→\n   265→## 8. KPI/SLO Framework\n   266→\n   267→### 8.1 Provisional vs normative thresholds\n   268→- Thresholds in current KPI table are **provisional** in shadow mode.\n   269→- They become **normative** only after calibration and explicit approval at phase gate.\n   270→\n   271→(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md` → KPI/SLO table note)\n   272→\n   273→### 8.2 Calibration method (normative)\n   274→1. Collect M1–M12 for at least two shadow windows.\n   275→2. Compute baseline distributions and replay stability.\n   276→3. Propose thresholds and warning/fail bands.\n   277→4. Obtain owner sign-off for normative activation at soft/full gate.\n   278→\n   279→(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md` → Shadow and phase gates)\n   280→\n   281→### 8.3 Warning/fail bands (authoritative examples)\n   282→- Runtime bands M1–M3 as defined in KPI table\n   283→- Determinism floor M4 strict by tier\n   284→- Evidence completeness M5 has no warning band (any miss is fail)\n   285→\n   286→(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md`)\n   287→\n   288→### 8.4 Heuristic operational guidance\n   289→If runtime degrades but determinism/evidence remain compliant, optimize check execution before relaxing policy thresholds.\n   290→\n   291→(Source: `metrics-and-gates.md` → Heuristic judgments)\n   292→\n   293→---\n   294→\n   295→## 9. Governance\n   296→\n   297→### 9.1 Override approval model (normative)\n   298→- Scope eligibility: task/milestone only\n   299→- Required approval metadata: approver identity, approval state, review due date\n   300→- Incomplete override metadata is invalid and blocks completion\n   301→\n   302→(Source: `05-review-checklist.md` → Section 6; `design-delta-v1.2.md` → Change 2; `metrics-and-gates.md` → M9)\n   303→\n   304→### 9.2 Owner responsibilities\n   305→- **Policy owner**: profile thresholds + severity mapping\n   306→- **State-machine owner**: legal/illegal transition validator correctness\n   307→- **Reliability owner**: timeout/retry/backoff + stale recovery\n   308→- **Migration owner**: rollout/rollback readiness and drills\n   309→- **Program manager**: open-decision closure with owner+deadline tracking\n   310→\n   311→(Source: `risk-register-v1.2.md` owners; `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` blockers)\n   312→\n   313→### 9.3 Decision deadlines (normative requirement)\n   314→All open blocking decisions must have:\n   315→- Owner\n   316→- UTC decision deadline\n   317→- Effective rollout phase\n   318→\n   319→No GO decision without all three assigned.\n   320→\n   321→(Source: `05-review-checklist.md` → Section 10; `executive-summary.md` → critical decisions; `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md`)\n   322→\n   323→---\n   324→\n   325→## 10. Implementation Mapping\n   326→\n   327→### 10.1 Phase plan\n   328→- **Phase 0**: design/policy lock and owner/date assignments\n   329→- **Phase 1**: deterministic contracts + evaluator + transition validator\n   330→- **Phase 2**: runtime controls (lease/heartbeat/retry/recovery)\n   331→- **Phase 3**: sprint CLI integration + override governance flow + report persistence\n   332→- **Phase 4**: rollout execution + KPI gates + rollback drills\n   333→\n   334→(Source: `implementation-plan-v1.2.md`)\n   335→\n   336→### 10.2 File-level change map (implementation target)\n   337→1. `src/superclaude/cli/sprint/models.py` — states/enums/constraints/profile fields\n   338→2. `src/superclaude/cli/sprint/tui.py` — completion/release guards and operator guidance\n   339→3. `src/superclaude/skills/sc-audit-gate/SKILL.md` — command behavior/profile/output contract\n   340→4. `src/superclaude/skills/sc-audit-gate-protocol/SKILL.md` — deterministic evaluator and transition legality/recovery flow\n   341→5. `src/superclaude/agents/*.md` — enrichment-only role clarification\n   342→6. `tests/sprint/test_audit_gate_state_machine.py` — legal/illegal transitions + stuck-state recovery\n   343→7. `tests/sprint/test_audit_gate_profiles.py` — profile determinism + severity behavior\n   344→8. `tests/sprint/test_audit_gate_overrides.py` — scope-limited override governance\n   345→9. `tests/sprint/test_audit_gate_rollout.py` — shadow/soft/full + rollback behavior\n   346→\n   347→(Source: `implementation-plan-v1.2.md` → File-level change map)\n   348→\n   349→### 10.3 Acceptance criteria per phase\n   350→- Phase 0: all blocking decisions closed with owner/date\n   351→- Phase 1: deterministic replay stability for same input; fail-safe unknown handling\n   352→- Phase 2: timeout/retry paths terminate deterministically (no deadlocks)\n   353→- Phase 3: transition blocking/override rules enforced per scope\n   354→- Phase 4: phase gates pass by KPI criteria and rollback drill success\n   355→\n   356→(Source: `implementation-plan-v1.2.md`; `metrics-and-gates.md`)\n   357→\n   358→---\n   359→\n   360→## 11. Checklist Closure Matrix (Sections 1–10)\n   361→\n   362→Source checklist: `05-review-checklist.md`.\n   363→\n   364→| Checklist section | Current status | Closure condition for GO | Evidence source |\n   365→|---|---|---|---|\n   366→| 1. Context completeness | PASS (conditional) | Assign owners/deadlines to open items | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` |\n   367→| 2. Command/API surface | PASS (conditional) | Approve canonical `--profile` and alias policy | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md`, `design-delta-v1.2.md` |\n   368→| 3. State machine/invariants | PASS (conditional) | Enforce legal/illegal transitions in implementation | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md`, `state-machine-validation.md` |\n   369→| 4. Data contracts | PASS (conditional) | Finalize event contracts + compatibility rules | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` |\n   370→| 5. Tier model soundness | PASS (conditional) | Finalize numeric thresholds + major severity behavior | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` |\n   371→| 6. Override/governance | PASS (conditional) | Finalize approver model + review cadence | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` |\n   372→| 7. Sprint CLI integration | PASS (conditional) | Integrate deterministic transition validator before completion transitions | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` |\n   373→| 8. Migration/backward compatibility | PASS (conditional) | Approve rollback/safe-disable trigger contract | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` |\n   374→| 9. Risk/reliability controls | PASS (conditional) | Finalize retry/backoff/timeout values and budgets | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md`, `risk-register-v1.2.md` |\n   375→| 10. Implementation readiness | NO-GO (current) | Close all 4 blockers with owner/date and reflect in artifacts | `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md`, `executive-summary.md` |\n   376→\n   377→---\n   378→\n   379→## 12. Final Release Decision Gate\n   380→\n   381→### 12.1 GO criteria\n   382→All must be true:\n   383→1. Blocking decisions closed (profile thresholds, major severity behavior, retry/backoff/timeout, rollback triggers)\n   384→2. Transition legality and recovery semantics implemented and tested\n   385→3. Deterministic contract and evidence completeness validated\n   386→4. Checklist sections 2,3,4,6,7 fully pass; remaining sections pass or have non-critical tracked gaps\n   387→5. Owners/deadlines assigned for any residual non-blocking items\n   388→\n   389→(Source: `05-review-checklist.md` → Minimum Acceptance Threshold + Section 10; `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md`)\n   390→\n   391→### 12.2 NO-GO criteria\n   392→Any one is sufficient:\n   393→- Any unresolved blocker from section 11\n   394→- Missing owner/deadline on blocking decision\n   395→- Determinism/evidence gate failure (M4/M5)\n   396→- Release override path exists or can be triggered\n   397→\n   398→(Source: `executive-summary.md`; `metrics-and-gates.md`; `01-requirements-spec.md`)\n   399→\n   400→### 12.3 Current blocker list\n   401→1. Profile thresholds and task-tier major-severity behavior not finalized\n   402→2. Retry/backoff/timeout values not finalized\n   403→3. Rollback/safe-disable triggers not finalized\n   404→4. Open blocking decisions not yet assigned owner+deadline in final artifact set\n   405→\n   406→(Source: `checklist-outcome-v1.2.md` → Blocking items)\n   407→\n   408→### 12.4 Required user decisions\n   409→1. Approve canonical profile model and numeric thresholds\n   410→2. Approve major-severity behavior at task tier under `standard`\n   411→3. Approve retry/backoff/timeout values and max attempts\n   412→4. Approve rollback/safe-disable objective triggers\n   413→5. Approve override governance model (single vs dual approver) and review cadence\n   414→\n   415→(Source: `executive-summary.md` → Critical decisions)\n   416→\n   417→---\n   418→\n   419→## Top 5 Immediate Actions\n   420→1. Finalize and sign off profile thresholds + major-severity behavior.\n   421→2. Finalize retry/backoff/timeout and stale-state budgets.\n   422→3. Ratify explicit legal/illegal transition table as implementation authority.\n   423→4. Approve rollback/safe-disable triggers and phase regression policy.\n   424→5. Assign owner + UTC deadline + effective phase to each blocking decision.\n   425→\n   426→## Top 5 Deferred Improvements\n   427→1. Add readiness preview mode pre-gate.\n   428→2. Improve human-readable remediation hints in gate failures.\n   429→3. Add trend dashboards for drift/override quality.\n   430→4. Add profile auto-tuning recommendations from shadow telemetry.\n   431→5. Optimize long-horizon artifact retention policy.\n   432→\n   433→## Open Decisions Needed from User\n   434→| Decision | Owner | Deadline (UTC) | Effective phase |\n   435→|---|---|---|---|\n   436→| Profile thresholds + major-severity behavior | [TBD] | [TBD] | Soft |\n   437→| Retry/backoff/timeout policy | [TBD] | [TBD] | Soft |\n   438→| Rollback/safe-disable triggers | [TBD] | [TBD] | Full |\n   439→| Override approver model + review cadence | [TBD] | [TBD] | Soft |\n   440→| `--strictness` alias deprecation date | [TBD] | [TBD] | Full |\n   441→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"uuid":"6912085d-7790-42ce-bcbd-bcc38f379d7b","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:35.435Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"bcece821-aa2e-4fab-9310-7b397a2740fb","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
{"parentUuid":"6912085d-7790-42ce-bcbd-bcc38f379d7b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9e3842d3be64b93d","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"call_hARfUphv8jR8fYl9WmfhvON0","toolUseID":"call_hARfUphv8jR8fYl9WmfhvON0","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:35.564Z","uuid":"30bfc35a-d057-4d29-a076-eb24d8c62be2","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
{"parentUuid":"a7ed239c-6892-4726-9fa3-bf21fc31bd82","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a9e3842d3be64b93d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_hARfUphv8jR8fYl9WmfhvON0","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→release: wiring-verification-gate-v1.0\n     3→version: 1.0.0\n     4→status: draft\n     5→date: 2026-03-17\n     6→parent_analysis: cli-portify-executor-noop-forensic-report.md\n     7→parent_ranking: proposal-ranking.md\n     8→fidelity_link: \"Link 3: Tasklist -> Code\"\n     9→priority: P0\n    10→estimated_scope: 300-400 lines production code\n    11→---\n    12→\n    13→# Wiring Verification Gate v1.0 -- Release Specification\n    14→\n    15→## 1. Problem Statement\n    16→\n    17→The cli-portify executor no-op bug (forensic report, 2026-03-17) demonstrated that\n    18→Link 3 of the fidelity chain (Tasklist -> Code) has zero programmatic coverage. The\n    19→pipeline's gate infrastructure validates documents -- not code integration. Components\n    20→defined in specifications and decomposed into tasks can pass all existing gates while\n    21→producing code where modules are never connected to their consumers.\n    22→\n    23→**The \"defined but not wired\" pattern recurs across multiple systems:**\n    24→\n    25→| System | Evidence |\n    26→|--------|----------|\n    27→| cli-portify executor | `step_runner=None` default; steps exist but are never called |\n    28→| DEVIATION_ANALYSIS_GATE | Defined at `roadmap/gates.py:712` but never wired into `_build_steps()` |\n    29→| SprintGatePolicy | Exists at `sprint/executor.py:46-89` but `build_remediation_step` is not invoked from the sprint loop |\n    30→| Trailing gate framework | `TrailingGateRunner` exists but `execute_sprint()` never calls it |\n    31→\n    32→**This release creates the first code-level gate in the pipeline.**\n    33→\n    34→---\n    35→\n    36→## 2. Goals and Non-Goals\n    37→\n    38→### Goals\n    39→\n    40→1. Detect unwired injectable dependencies (`Optional[Callable] = None` never provided at any call site)\n    41→2. Detect orphan modules (exported functions never imported by any consumer)\n    42→3. Detect unwired dispatch registries (dictionary entries mapping to non-importable functions)\n    43→4. Emit a structured YAML report compatible with the `GateCriteria`/`SemanticCheck` pattern\n    44→5. Deploy in shadow mode initially, with a path to soft and full enforcement\n    45→\n    46→### Non-Goals (v1.0)\n    47→\n    48→- No-op fallback detection (deferred to v1.1 pending shadow-mode data)\n    49→- Cross-language analysis (Python only)\n    50→- Runtime behavioral verification (see Smoke Test Gate proposal)\n    51→- Dynamic dispatch resolution (`**kwargs`, `getattr`, `importlib`)\n    52→- Modifying the `SemanticCheck` interface (no `pre_checks` in this release)\n    53→\n    54→---\n    55→\n    56→## 3. Architecture\n    57→\n    58→### 3.1 System Context\n    59→\n    60→```\n    61→Existing Pipeline Infrastructure          New Component\n    62→================================          =============\n    63→\n    64→pipeline/models.py                        audit/wiring_gate.py\n    65→  GateCriteria ─────────────────────────>   WIRING_GATE (constant)\n    66→  SemanticCheck ────────────────────────>   check functions\n    67→\n    68→pipeline/gates.py\n    69→  gate_passed() ────────────────────────>   evaluates WIRING_GATE\n    70→\n    71→sprint/executor.py\n    72→  SprintGatePolicy ─────────────────────>   invokes wiring checks post-task\n    73→\n    74→pipeline/trailing_gate.py\n    75→  TrailingGateRunner ───────────────────>   deferred evaluation (shadow mode)\n    76→  resolve_gate_mode() ──────────────────>   scope-aware enforcement\n    77→```\n    78→\n    79→### 3.2 Module Architecture\n    80→\n    81→```\n    82→src/superclaude/cli/audit/wiring_gate.py    (NEW -- core analysis)\n    83→    |\n    84→    |--- WiringFinding (dataclass)\n    85→    |--- WiringReport (dataclass)\n    86→    |--- analyze_unwired_callables(paths) -> list[WiringFinding]\n    87→    |--- analyze_orphan_modules(paths, root) -> list[WiringFinding]\n    88→    |--- analyze_unwired_registries(paths) -> list[WiringFinding]\n    89→    |--- run_wiring_analysis(target_dir) -> WiringReport\n    90→    |--- emit_report(report, output_path) -> None\n    91→    |--- check_wiring_report(content: str) -> bool    # SemanticCheck-compatible\n    92→    |\n    93→    |--- WIRING_GATE = GateCriteria(...)              # gate definition\n    94→\n    95→src/superclaude/cli/audit/wiring_config.py  (NEW -- configuration)\n    96→    |\n    97→    |--- WiringConfig (dataclass)\n    98→    |--- DEFAULT_REGISTRY_PATTERNS\n    99→    |--- DEFAULT_WHITELIST\n   100→    |--- load_wiring_config(path) -> WiringConfig\n   101→```\n   102→\n   103→### 3.3 Data Flow\n   104→\n   105→```\n   106→                    +-----------------+\n   107→                    | Task completes  |\n   108→                    | (sprint runner) |\n   109→                    +--------+--------+\n   110→                             |\n   111→                             v\n   112→                    +--------+--------+\n   113→                    | Collect changed |\n   114→                    | file paths      |\n   115→                    | (git diff)      |\n   116→                    +--------+--------+\n   117→                             |\n   118→                             v\n   119→                +------------+------------+\n   120→                | run_wiring_analysis()   |\n   121→                |                         |\n   122→                | 1. analyze_unwired_     |\n   123→                |    callables()          |\n   124→                | 2. analyze_orphan_      |\n   125→                |    modules()            |\n   126→                | 3. analyze_unwired_     |\n   127→                |    registries()         |\n   128→                +------------+------------+\n   129→                             |\n   130→                             v\n   131→                +------------+------------+\n   132→                | emit_report()           |\n   133→                | -> wiring-report.md     |\n   134→                | (YAML frontmatter +     |\n   135→                |  finding details)       |\n   136→                +------------+------------+\n   137→                             |\n   138→                             v\n   139→                +------------+------------+\n   140→                | gate_passed(            |\n   141→                |   wiring-report.md,     |\n   142→                |   WIRING_GATE           |\n   143→                | )                       |\n   144→                +------------+------------+\n   145→                             |\n   146→                    +--------+--------+\n   147→                    |  shadow: log    |\n   148→                    |  soft: warn     |\n   149→                    |  full: block    |\n   150→                    +--------+--------+\n   151→```\n   152→\n   153→---\n   154→\n   155→## 4. Detailed Design\n   156→\n   157→### 4.1 Data Models\n   158→\n   159→```python\n   160→# src/superclaude/cli/audit/wiring_gate.py\n   161→\n   162→from __future__ import annotations\n   163→\n   164→import ast\n   165→import re\n   166→from dataclasses import dataclass, field\n   167→from pathlib import Path\n   168→from typing import Literal\n   169→\n   170→from ..pipeline.models import GateCriteria, SemanticCheck\n   171→\n   172→\n   173→@dataclass\n   174→class WiringFinding:\n   175→    \"\"\"A single wiring verification finding.\"\"\"\n   176→\n   177→    finding_type: Literal[\"unwired_callable\", \"orphan_module\", \"unwired_registry\"]\n   178→    file_path: str\n   179→    symbol_name: str\n   180→    line_number: int\n   181→    detail: str\n   182→    severity: Literal[\"critical\", \"major\"] = \"critical\"\n   183→\n   184→    def to_dict(self) -> dict[str, str | int]:\n   185→        return {\n   186→            \"finding_type\": self.finding_type,\n   187→            \"file_path\": self.file_path,\n   188→            \"symbol_name\": self.symbol_name,\n   189→            \"line_number\": self.line_number,\n   190→            \"detail\": self.detail,\n   191→            \"severity\": self.severity,\n   192→        }\n   193→\n   194→\n   195→@dataclass\n   196→class WiringReport:\n   197→    \"\"\"Aggregate wiring analysis results.\"\"\"\n   198→\n   199→    target_dir: str\n   200→    files_analyzed: int = 0\n   201→    unwired_callables: list[WiringFinding] = field(default_factory=list)\n   202→    orphan_modules: list[WiringFinding] = field(default_factory=list)\n   203→    unwired_registries: list[WiringFinding] = field(default_factory=list)\n   204→\n   205→    @property\n   206→    def unwired_count(self) -> int:\n   207→        return len(self.unwired_callables)\n   208→\n   209→    @property\n   210→    def orphan_count(self) -> int:\n   211→        return len(self.orphan_modules)\n   212→\n   213→    @property\n   214→    def registry_count(self) -> int:\n   215→        return len(self.unwired_registries)\n   216→\n   217→    @property\n   218→    def total_findings(self) -> int:\n   219→        return self.unwired_count + self.orphan_count + self.registry_count\n   220→\n   221→    @property\n   222→    def passed(self) -> bool:\n   223→        return self.total_findings == 0\n   224→```\n   225→\n   226→### 4.2 Analysis Functions\n   227→\n   228→#### 4.2.1 Unwired Callable Analysis\n   229→\n   230→**Purpose**: Detect constructor parameters typed `Optional[Callable]` (or `Callable | None`)\n   231→with default `None` that are never explicitly provided at any call site in the codebase.\n   232→\n   233→**Algorithm**:\n   234→\n   235→```\n   236→1. AST-parse all Python files in target directory\n   237→2. For each class definition:\n   238→   a. Find __init__ method\n   239→   b. Extract parameters where annotation references Callable with a None default:\n   240→\n   241→      Normalize annotation to string:\n   242→        annotation_str = ast.unparse(param.annotation) if param.annotation else \"\"\n   243→\n   244→      Match using word-boundary pattern (prevents false positives on names\n   245→      containing \"Callable\" as a substring, e.g., NotCallableType):\n   246→        callable_pattern = re.compile(\n   247→            r'\\b(typing\\.)?Callable\\b|'\n   248→            r'\\bcollections\\.abc\\.Callable\\b'\n   249→        )\n   250→\n   251→      Record as injectable if:\n   252→        callable_pattern.search(annotation_str)\n   253→        AND isinstance(param.default, ast.Constant)\n   254→        AND param.default.value is None\n   255→\n   256→      Note: ast.unparse() handles all annotation forms correctly, including\n   257→      ast.Subscript nodes (Optional[Callable[...]]) and manually-quoted\n   258→      forward references (\"Callable[...]\") which render as quoted literals\n   259→      still matchable by the pattern above.\n   260→      Note: from __future__ import annotations does NOT change ast.parse()\n   261→      output — annotations remain AST nodes in all Python versions.\n   262→      No runtime annotation evaluation is required or appropriate here.\n   263→\n   264→   c. Record as injectable: (class_name, param_name, file_path, line)\n   265→3. For each injectable found:\n   266→   a. Search all Python files for call sites constructing that class\n   267→   b. Check if any call site provides the parameter by keyword\n   268→   c. If zero call sites provide it -> WiringFinding(unwired_callable)\n   269→```\n   270→\n   271→**Known Limitation — Import Aliases and Re-exports (tracked for v1.1)**\n   272→\n   273→The call-site search matches class names as they appear in the defining module.\n   274→Classes re-exported through `__init__.py` and consumed via aliases\n   275→(e.g., `from package import ClassName` where the package `__init__.py`\n   276→re-exports it) will not be resolved. This produces false positives for\n   277→re-exported classes.\n   278→\n   279→Expected FPR contribution in codebases using package-level re-exports:\n   280→30–70% of unwired-callable findings in shadow mode may be re-export false\n   281→positives. Phase 2 thresholds must be calibrated against Phase 1 data with\n   282→this in mind (see Section 8 threshold calibration guidance).\n   283→\n   284→Planned fix (v1.1): pre-pass alias map construction via `ast.Import` /\n   285→`ast.ImportFrom` traversal with `__init__.py` chain resolution (max 3 hops).\n   286→\n   287→**Pattern matched** (from forensic report):\n   288→```python\n   289→# This triggers detection:\n   290→class PortifyExecutor:\n   291→    def __init__(self, ..., step_runner: Optional[Callable] = None):\n   292→        ...\n   293→\n   294→# This call site does NOT provide step_runner:\n   295→executor = PortifyExecutor(steps=steps, workdir=workdir, ...)\n   296→# -> Finding: unwired_callable, PortifyExecutor.step_runner\n   297→```\n   298→\n   299→**Whitelist mechanism**: A `wiring_whitelist.yaml` file can list intentionally-optional\n   300→callables (event hooks, logging callbacks) excluded from analysis.\n   301→\n   302→**Schema**: each entry must conform to:\n   303→\n   304→```yaml\n   305→# wiring_whitelist.yaml\n   306→unwired_callables:\n   307→  - symbol: \"module.path.ClassName.param_name\"  # required; dotted path\n   308→    reason: \"string\"                             # required; non-empty\n   309→```\n   310→\n   311→The legacy `class` + `param` split form is accepted as equivalent to\n   312→`symbol: \"ClassName.param\"` and normalized on load.\n   313→\n   314→**Validation behavior (Phase 1 — shadow mode)**:\n   315→- `load_wiring_config()` MUST validate each entry against the schema above.\n   316→- Entries missing `symbol` or `reason`, or with an empty `reason`, are MALFORMED.\n   317→  Malformed entries MUST be skipped with a WARNING:\n   318→    `WARNING: wiring_whitelist.yaml entry [N] malformed (missing: <field>), skipping.`\n   319→- `load_wiring_config()` MUST NOT raise `WiringConfigError` for malformed entries\n   320→  during Phase 1 shadow mode — the gate must continue running to preserve\n   321→  observation data.\n   322→\n   323→**Phase 2 note**: `load_wiring_config()` will be updated to raise `WiringConfigError`\n   324→on any malformed entry before Phase 2 activation. Resolve all whitelist warnings\n   325→before Phase 2 cutover.\n   326→\n   327→#### 4.2.2 Orphan Module Analysis\n   328→\n   329→**Purpose**: Detect Python files in conventionally-structured directories (`steps/`,\n   330→`handlers/`, `validators/`) whose exported functions are never imported by any\n   331→consumer module.\n   332→\n   333→**Algorithm**:\n   334→\n   335→```\n   336→1. Identify \"provider directories\" by convention:\n   337→   - directories named steps/, handlers/, validators/, checks/\n   338→   - directories containing 3+ Python files with a common function prefix\n   339→2. For each Python file in a provider directory:\n   340→   a. AST-parse to extract top-level function definitions (excluding _private)\n   341→   b. For each exported function:\n   342→      - Search all Python files OUTSIDE the provider directory for:\n   343→        * import statements referencing the function\n   344→        * from ... import statements referencing the function\n   345→   c. If zero importers found -> WiringFinding(orphan_module)\n   346→```\n   347→\n   348→**Pattern matched** (from forensic report):\n   349→```python\n   350→# src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify/steps/validate_config.py\n   351→def run_validate_config():  # exported, but never imported by executor.py\n   352→    ...\n   353→\n   354→# executor.py never contains:\n   355→# from .steps.validate_config import run_validate_config\n   356→# -> Finding: orphan_module, steps/validate_config.py::run_validate_config\n   357→```\n   358→\n   359→**Exclusions**: `__init__.py`, files matching `conftest.py`, `test_*.py`.\n   360→\n   361→#### 4.2.3 Unwired Registry Analysis\n   362→\n   363→**Purpose**: Detect dictionary constants with naming patterns indicating dispatch\n   364→registries (`REGISTRY`, `DISPATCH`, `RUNNERS`, `HANDLERS`, `ROUTER`) whose values\n   365→reference functions that cannot be resolved via import.\n   366→\n   367→**Algorithm**:\n   368→\n   369→```\n   370→1. AST-parse all Python files\n   371→2. For each module-level assignment where:\n   372→   a. Target name matches REGISTRY_PATTERNS regex\n   373→   b. Value is a Dict literal\n   374→3. For each dict entry:\n   375→   a. Extract value (expected: function reference or string path)\n   376→   b. If value is a Name node: verify the name is importable in scope\n   377→   c. If value is a string: verify it resolves to a module.function path\n   378→4. Entries with unresolvable values -> WiringFinding(unwired_registry)\n   379→```\n   380→\n   381→**Registry patterns** (configurable):\n   382→```python\n   383→DEFAULT_REGISTRY_PATTERNS = re.compile(\n   384→    r\"^(STEP_REGISTRY|STEP_DISPATCH|PROGRAMMATIC_RUNNERS|\"\n   385→    r\"\\w*_REGISTRY|\\w*_DISPATCH|\\w*_HANDLERS|\\w*_ROUTER)$\"\n   386→)\n   387→```\n   388→\n   389→### 4.3 Report Format\n   390→\n   391→The wiring analysis emits a Markdown file with YAML frontmatter, conforming to\n   392→the `GateCriteria` validation pattern used by all existing gates.\n   393→\n   394→```markdown\n   395→---\n   396→gate: wiring-verification\n   397→target_dir: src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify\n   398→files_analyzed: 14\n   399→unwired_count: 1\n   400→orphan_count: 2\n   401→registry_count: 0\n   402→total_findings: 3\n   403→analysis_complete: true\n   404→enforcement_mode: shadow\n   405→---\n   406→\n   407→# Wiring Verification Report\n   408→\n   409→## Unwired Callables (1)\n   410→\n   411→### WF-001: PortifyExecutor.step_runner\n   412→\n   413→- **File**: src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify/executor.py\n   414→- **Line**: 393\n   415→- **Type**: unwired_callable\n   416→- **Severity**: critical\n   417→- **Detail**: Constructor parameter `step_runner: Optional[Callable] = None` is never\n   418→  provided at any of 1 call sites. Call sites: `executor.py:1395 (run_portify)`.\n   419→\n   420→## Orphan Modules (2)\n   421→\n   422→### WF-002: steps/validate_config.py::run_validate_config\n   423→\n   424→- **File**: src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify/steps/validate_config.py\n   425→- **Line**: 12\n   426→- **Type**: orphan_module\n   427→- **Severity**: critical\n   428→- **Detail**: Exported function `run_validate_config` has 0 importers across 14 files.\n   429→\n   430→### WF-003: steps/discover_components.py::run_discover_components\n   431→\n   432→- **File**: src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify/steps/discover_components.py\n   433→- **Line**: 8\n   434→- **Type**: orphan_module\n   435→- **Severity**: critical\n   436→- **Detail**: Exported function `run_discover_components` has 0 importers across 14 files.\n   437→\n   438→## Summary\n   439→\n   440→3 findings (1 unwired callable, 2 orphan modules, 0 unwired registries).\n   441→Gate status: FAIL (enforcement: shadow -- logged only).\n   442→```\n   443→\n   444→**4.3.1 Frontmatter Serialization Requirements**\n   445→\n   446→The `emit_report` function (T05) MUST serialize all string-valued frontmatter\n   447→fields using `yaml.safe_dump()` rather than f-string or `str.format()` interpolation.\n   448→This applies to: `target_dir`, `symbol_name`, `detail`.\n   449→\n   450→Boolean and integer fields that are gate-evaluated (`analysis_complete`,\n   451→`unwired_count`, `orphan_count`, `registry_count`, `total_findings`) are\n   452→serialized as Python literals and are exempt from this requirement.\n   453→\n   454→**Rationale**: f-string interpolation of filesystem paths and symbol names into\n   455→YAML produces malformed output when values contain YAML-special characters (`:`,\n   456→`|`, `{`, `}`, `[`, `]`). While these cannot appear in Python identifiers, they\n   457→can appear in `target_dir` values. Malformed frontmatter causes report parse\n   458→errors; defensively handled, these produce gate failures rather than bypasses,\n   459→but the failure mode is confusing and avoidable.\n   460→\n   461→**Implementation pattern**:\n   462→```python\n   463→import yaml\n   464→metadata_fields = {\n   465→    \"target_dir\": str(target_dir),\n   466→    \"symbol_name\": finding.symbol_name,\n   467→    \"detail\": finding.detail,\n   468→}\n   469→frontmatter_str = yaml.safe_dump(metadata_fields, default_flow_style=False)\n   470→```\n   471→\n   472→**4.3.2 Whitelist Audit Visibility in Frontmatter**\n   473→\n   474→`emit_report()` MUST include the following field in YAML frontmatter:\n   475→\n   476→```yaml\n   477→whitelist_entries_applied: 0   # integer; count of entries that suppressed ≥1 finding\n   478→```\n   479→\n   480→This field is required regardless of whether a whitelist file is configured.\n   481→If no whitelist is configured or no entries matched, emit `whitelist_entries_applied: 0`.\n   482→\n   483→**Rationale**: reviewers must be able to detect whitelist-based suppression from\n   484→the gate report alone, without diffing `wiring_whitelist.yaml` across commits.\n   485→\n   486→### 4.4 Gate Definition\n   487→\n   488→```python\n   489→WIRING_GATE = GateCriteria(\n   490→    required_frontmatter_fields=[\n   491→        \"gate\",\n   492→        \"target_dir\",\n   493→        \"files_analyzed\",\n   494→        \"unwired_count\",\n   495→        \"orphan_count\",\n   496→        \"registry_count\",\n   497→        \"total_findings\",\n   498→        \"analysis_complete\",\n   499→        \"enforcement_mode\",\n   500→        \"whitelist_entries_applied\",\n   501→    ],\n   502→    min_lines=10,\n   503→    enforcement_tier=\"STRICT\",\n   504→    semantic_checks=[\n   505→        SemanticCheck(\n   506→            name=\"analysis_complete_true\",\n   507→            check_fn=_analysis_complete_true,\n   508→            failure_message=\"analysis_complete must be true\",\n   509→        ),\n   510→        SemanticCheck(\n   511→            name=\"zero_unwired_callables\",\n   512→            check_fn=_zero_unwired_callables,\n   513→            failure_message=\"unwired_count must be 0; all injectable callables must be provided\",\n   514→        ),\n   515→        SemanticCheck(\n   516→            name=\"zero_orphan_modules\",\n   517→            check_fn=_zero_orphan_modules,\n   518→            failure_message=\"orphan_count must be 0; all exported functions must have importers\",\n   519→        ),\n   520→        SemanticCheck(\n   521→            name=\"zero_unwired_registries\",\n   522→            check_fn=_zero_unwired_registries,\n   523→            failure_message=\"registry_count must be 0; all registry entries must resolve\",\n   524→        ),\n   525→        SemanticCheck(\n   526→            name=\"total_findings_consistent\",\n   527→            check_fn=_total_findings_consistent,\n   528→            failure_message=\"total_findings must equal unwired_count + orphan_count + registry_count\",\n   529→        ),\n   530→    ],\n   531→)\n   532→```\n   533→\n   534→The semantic check functions follow the established `(content: str) -> bool` pattern\n   535→used by `_high_severity_count_zero`, `_total_analyzed_consistent`, etc. in `roadmap/gates.py`.\n   536→\n   537→### 4.5 Sprint Integration\n   538→\n   539→The wiring gate hooks into the sprint runner at the post-task classification point.\n   540→\n   541→**Hook point**: `sprint/executor.py`, after `_classify_from_result_file()` returns,\n   542→before the task status is finalized.\n   543→\n   544→**Shadow mode flow** (v1.0 default):\n   545→\n   546→```python\n   547→# In execute_phase_tasks() or _run_task_subprocess(), after classification:\n   548→\n   549→wiring_report_path = work_dir / f\"{task_id}-wiring-report.md\"\n   550→report = run_wiring_analysis(target_dir=config.source_dir)\n   551→emit_report(report, wiring_report_path)\n   552→\n   553→if config.wiring_gate_mode == \"shadow\":\n   554→    # Log result but do not affect task status\n   555→    logger.info(f\"[shadow] Wiring gate: {report.total_findings} findings\")\n   556→elif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"soft\":\n   557→    # Warn in TUI but do not block\n   558→    if not report.passed:\n   559→        tui.warn(f\"Wiring gate: {report.total_findings} findings\")\n   560→elif config.wiring_gate_mode == \"full\":\n   561→    # Block task completion\n   562→    passed, reason = gate_passed(wiring_report_path, WIRING_GATE)\n   563→    if not passed:\n   564→        # Trigger remediation via SprintGatePolicy\n   565→        ...\n   566→```\n   567→\n   568→**Configuration**: New field on `SprintConfig`:\n   569→\n   570→```python\n   571→wiring_gate_mode: Literal[\"off\", \"shadow\", \"soft\", \"full\"] = \"shadow\"\n   572→```\n   573→\n   574→### 4.6 Companion: Deviation Count Reconciliation\n   575→\n   576→This release also includes the Deviation Count Reconciliation Gate (Proposal 4 from\n   577→the ranking), as a zero-cost companion that strengthens existing Link 1 gates.\n   578→\n   579→**Implementation**: Single function `_deviation_counts_reconciled(content: str) -> bool`\n   580→added to `SPEC_FIDELITY_GATE.semantic_checks` in `roadmap/gates.py`.\n   581→\n   582→**Algorithm**:\n   583→1. Parse frontmatter for `high_severity_count`, `medium_severity_count`, `low_severity_count`\n   584→2. Regex-scan body for `DEV-\\d{3}` entries, extract severity from `**Severity**: X` lines\n   585→3. Compare body counts to frontmatter counts\n   586→4. Fail on any mismatch\n   587→\n   588→**Estimated LOC**: 35-50 lines.\n   589→\n   590→---\n   591→\n   592→## 5. File Manifest\n   593→\n   594→| File | Action | Estimated LOC | Purpose |\n   595→|------|--------|---------------|---------|\n   596→| `src/superclaude/cli/audit/wiring_gate.py` | CREATE | 250-300 | Core analysis engine, report emitter, gate definition |\n   597→| `src/superclaude/cli/audit/wiring_config.py` | CREATE | 40-60 | Configuration dataclass, patterns, whitelist loader |\n   598→| `src/superclaude/cli/sprint/config.py` | MODIFY | +5 | Add `wiring_gate_mode` field |\n   599→| `src/superclaude/cli/sprint/executor.py` | MODIFY | +25 | Post-task wiring analysis hook |\n   600→| `src/superclaude/cli/roadmap/gates.py` | MODIFY | +40 | `_deviation_counts_reconciled` semantic check |\n   601→| `tests/audit/test_wiring_gate.py` | CREATE | 200-250 | Unit tests for all analysis functions |\n   602→| `tests/audit/test_deviation_recon.py` | CREATE | 60-80 | Unit tests for deviation count reconciliation |\n   603→| `tests/audit/fixtures/` | CREATE | 50-80 | Python fixtures for wiring analysis tests |\n   604→\n   605→**Total new production code**: ~360-430 lines\n   606→**Total new test code**: ~310-410 lines\n   607→\n   608→---\n   609→\n   610→## 6. Interface Contracts\n   611→\n   612→### 6.1 Public API\n   613→\n   614→```python\n   615→# Entry point for wiring analysis\n   616→def run_wiring_analysis(\n   617→    target_dir: Path,\n   618→    config: WiringConfig | None = None,\n   619→) -> WiringReport:\n   620→    \"\"\"Analyze a directory for wiring verification issues.\n   621→\n   622→    Args:\n   623→        target_dir: Root directory to analyze (e.g., src/superclaude/cli/cli_portify/).\n   624→        config: Optional configuration overriding defaults.\n   625→\n   626→    Returns:\n   627→        WiringReport with all findings.\n   628→    \"\"\"\n   629→\n   630→# Report emitter (Markdown + YAML frontmatter)\n   631→def emit_report(\n   632→    report: WiringReport,\n   633→    output_path: Path,\n   634→    enforcement_mode: str = \"shadow\",\n   635→) -> None:\n   636→    \"\"\"Write wiring report as Markdown with YAML frontmatter.\n   637→\n   638→    The output conforms to the GateCriteria validation pattern:\n   639→    frontmatter fields match WIRING_GATE.required_frontmatter_fields.\n   640→    \"\"\"\n   641→\n   642→# SemanticCheck-compatible function\n   643→def check_wiring_report(content: str) -> bool:\n   644→    \"\"\"Validate a wiring report passes all criteria.\n   645→\n   646→    Used as check_fn in SemanticCheck instances on WIRING_GATE.\n   647→    \"\"\"\n   648→```\n   649→\n   650→### 6.2 Configuration Contract\n   651→\n   652→```python\n   653→@dataclass\n   654→class WiringConfig:\n   655→    \"\"\"Configuration for wiring verification analysis.\"\"\"\n   656→\n   657→    # Patterns identifying dispatch registries\n   658→    registry_patterns: re.Pattern = DEFAULT_REGISTRY_PATTERNS\n   659→\n   660→    # Directories treated as \"provider\" directories for orphan analysis.\n   661→    # IMPORTANT: must be set to match the target repository's actual provider\n   662→    # directory conventions before shadow mode activation.\n   663→    # The default value {\"steps\", \"handlers\", \"validators\", \"checks\"} reflects\n   664→    # common framework conventions and will produce zero orphan findings (a false\n   665→    # clean result) in codebases using different naming (e.g., \"audit/\",\n   666→    # \"execution/\", \"pm_agent/\"). This field is not optional for production deployments.\n   667→    # See Section 8 pre-activation checklist.\n   668→    provider_dir_names: frozenset[str] = frozenset({\n   669→        \"steps\", \"handlers\", \"validators\", \"checks\",\n   670→    })\n   671→\n   672→    # Path to wiring_whitelist.yaml. Entries suppress gate findings for matched symbols.\n   673→    # See Section 4.2.1 for entry schema and validation behavior.\n   674→    # Count of applied entries is reported in gate output frontmatter (Section 4.3.2).\n   675→    whitelist_path: Path | None = None\n   676→\n   677→    # File exclusion patterns\n   678→    exclude_patterns: list[str] = field(default_factory=lambda: [\n   679→        \"test_*.py\", \"conftest.py\", \"__init__.py\",\n   680→    ])\n   681→```\n   682→\n   683→### 6.3 Gate Contract\n   684→\n   685→The `WIRING_GATE` constant conforms to `GateCriteria` and is evaluated by the\n   686→existing `gate_passed()` function in `pipeline/gates.py` without modification.\n   687→\n   688→**Frontmatter contract** (must appear in every report):\n   689→\n   690→| Field | Type | Constraint |\n   691→|-------|------|-----------|\n   692→| `gate` | string | Must be `\"wiring-verification\"` |\n   693→| `target_dir` | string | Non-empty |\n   694→| `files_analyzed` | int | >= 0 |\n   695→| `unwired_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   696→| `orphan_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   697→| `registry_count` | int | Must be 0 for gate pass |\n   698→| `total_findings` | int | Must equal sum of above three |\n   699→| `analysis_complete` | bool | Must be true |\n   700→| `whitelist_entries_applied` | int | >= 0; count of whitelist entries that suppressed findings |\n   701→\n   702→---\n   703→\n   704→## 7. Risk Assessment\n   705→\n   706→| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n   707→|------|-----------|--------|-----------|\n   708→| R1: False positives from intentional `Optional[Callable]` hooks | High | Medium | Whitelist mechanism (`wiring_whitelist.yaml`) |\n   709→| R2: AST parsing fails on complex Python patterns | Medium | Low | Graceful degradation: log warning, skip file, do not fail gate |\n   710→| R3: Shadow mode collects insufficient data | Low | Medium | Shadow mode runs for minimum 2 releases before enforcement decision |\n   711→| R4: Performance impact on sprint loop | Low | Medium | Wiring analysis is AST-only, no subprocess; expected < 2s for 50-file packages |\n   712→| R5: Naming convention heuristics miss new registry patterns | Medium | Low | Configurable `registry_patterns` regex; log when no registries found |\n   713→| R6: `provider_dir_names` mismatch with actual codebase conventions | High | High | Pre-activation validation checklist (Section 8 Phase 1); zero-findings sanity check required on first run |\n   714→\n   715→---\n   716→\n   717→## 8. Rollout Plan\n   718→\n   719→### Phase 1: Shadow (this release)\n   720→\n   721→**Pre-activation checklist (blocking — shadow mode must not start until both pass):**\n   722→\n   723→1. **Provider directory validation**: Confirm that at least one directory matching\n   724→   `provider_dir_names` exists in the target repository and contains at least one\n   725→   Python file. If zero matches are found, update `provider_dir_names` in\n   726→   `WiringConfig` before proceeding. A shadow run against a misconfigured\n   727→   `provider_dir_names` produces a silent null result indistinguishable from a\n   728→   genuinely clean codebase and corrupts baseline data.\n   729→\n   730→2. **Zero-findings sanity check**: If the first shadow run produces zero findings\n   731→   across ALL analyzers on a repository with >50 Python files, treat this as a\n   732→   configuration error requiring investigation, not a passing result.\n   733→   Log `WARN: zero-findings-on-first-run` and halt baseline collection until\n   734→   the configuration is verified.\n   735→\n   736→- Wiring analysis runs after every task in sprint execution\n   737→- Results logged to `.sprint-state/wiring/` directory\n   738→- No impact on task status or pipeline flow\n   739→- Collect baseline: false positive rate, finding distribution, analysis time\n   740→\n   741→### Phase 2: Soft (release +1, pending shadow data review)\n   742→\n   743→- Findings surfaced as warnings in sprint TUI\n   744→- Findings recorded in `DeferredRemediationLog`\n   745→- Block only at release scope (per `resolve_gate_mode()` which returns BLOCKING for release)\n   746→- Override available via `--skip-wiring-gate` flag\n   747→\n   748→**Threshold calibration for known FPR sources**:\n   749→\n   750→When setting Phase 2 activation thresholds from Phase 1 baseline data,\n   751→explicitly account for the following known false-positive sources:\n   752→\n   753→| Source | Expected FPR contribution | v1.0 mitigation | Planned fix |\n   754→|---|---|---|---|\n   755→| Re-exported classes (import aliases) | 30–70% of unwired-callable findings | Raise Phase 2 unwired-callable threshold; document noise floor | v1.1 alias pre-pass |\n   756→| `provider_dir_names` misconfiguration | 100% of orphan-module findings (silent) | Pre-activation validation checklist (Section 8 Phase 1) | N/A — config |\n   757→\n   758→**Decision rule**: Phase 2 MUST NOT be activated if Phase 1 unwired-callable\n   759→FPR cannot be separated from the re-export noise floor. Document the estimated\n   760→noise floor in the Phase 1 report. Set Phase 2 thresholds at\n   761→`measured_FPR + 2σ` above the noise floor estimate, not above zero.\n   762→\n   763→### Phase 3: Full (release +2, pending soft data review)\n   764→\n   765→- Findings block task completion at STRICT tier\n   766→- Remediation via `SprintGatePolicy.build_remediation_step()`\n   767→- No override without explicit whitelist entry\n   768→\n   769→### Rollout Decision Criteria\n   770→\n   771→| Metric | Shadow -> Soft Threshold | Soft -> Full Threshold |\n   772→|--------|--------------------------|------------------------|\n   773→| False positive rate | < 15% of findings are whitelisted | < 5% |\n   774→| True positive rate | > 50% of findings are genuine bugs | > 80% |\n   775→| Analysis time p95 | < 5 seconds | < 3 seconds |\n   776→| Whitelist stability | Whitelist unchanged for 2+ sprints | Whitelist unchanged for 5+ sprints |\n   777→\n   778→---\n   779→\n   780→## 9. Testing Strategy\n   781→\n   782→### 9.1 Coverage Requirements\n   783→\n   784→The test suite shall validate the wiring analysis gate across two layers.\n   785→\n   786→#### Unit Tests (minimum 14 tests, across 4 analyzer functions)\n   787→\n   788→**analyze_unwired_callables** (minimum 4 tests):\n   789→- Positive: detects a callable parameter with `Optional[Callable] = None` that\n   790→  has zero call sites providing it — produces 1 `WiringFinding(unwired_callable)`\n   791→- Negative: same class, call site provides the parameter by keyword —\n   792→  produces 0 findings\n   793→- Whitelist: parameter matches a whitelist entry — produces 0 findings\n   794→- Parse error: source file with a Python syntax error — gate does not crash;\n   795→  logs a warning; `analysis_complete` field reflects degraded state\n   796→- **Out of scope** (dynamic dispatch exclusion, Section 2): alias-based\n   797→  injection and `**kwargs`-forwarded injection do not require test cases\n   798→\n   799→**analyze_orphan_modules** (minimum 5 tests):\n   800→- Positive: function in a provider directory with zero importers —\n   801→  produces 1 `WiringFinding(orphan_module)`\n   802→- Negative (direct import): same function, explicitly imported by consumer —\n   803→  produces 0 findings\n   804→- Negative (`__init__.py` re-export): function re-exported via package\n   805→  `__init__.py` and consumed transitively — produces 0 findings\n   806→- Private function (`_name` prefix): excluded from analysis — produces 0 findings\n   807→- `conftest.py`: pytest infrastructure files excluded — produces 0 findings\n   808→\n   809→**analyze_unwired_registries** (minimum 2 tests):\n   810→- Positive: registry entry whose value symbol cannot be resolved —\n   811→  produces 1 `WiringFinding(unwired_registry)`\n   812→- Negative: registry entry whose value symbol resolves correctly —\n   813→  produces 0 findings\n   814→\n   815→**emit_report / gate** (minimum 3 tests):\n   816→- Findings present → `gate_passed()` returns `(False, reason)`; report\n   817→  frontmatter has non-zero count fields\n   818→- No findings → `gate_passed()` returns `(True, None)`; report frontmatter\n   819→  has all count fields == 0\n   820→- YAML-safe serialization: a report emitted when `target_dir` contains a\n   821→  YAML-special character (e.g., colon) and `symbol_name` contains a block\n   822→  indicator character must parse without `yaml.YAMLError`; `gate_passed()`\n   823→  must return the expected result based on finding counts\n   824→\n   825→### 9.2 Integration Tests (minimum 2 tests)\n   826→\n   827→**SC-010: cli-portify fixture integration**\n   828→\n   829→A dedicated fixture module set shall exist under `tests/audit/fixtures/`.\n   830→The fixture must contain:\n   831→- A source file defining a class with a constructor parameter typed\n   832→  `Optional[Callable]` with a `None` default\n   833→- A second source file that instantiates that class without providing the\n   834→  callable parameter\n   835→\n   836→Behavioral contract (non-negotiable): `run_wiring_analysis()` on the fixture\n   837→directory MUST produce exactly 1 `WiringFinding` of type `\"unwired_callable\"`\n   838→identifying the specific class and parameter. Zero findings or more than 1\n   839→finding constitutes test failure.\n   840→\n   841→The fixture file structure, class names, parameter names, and module layout\n   842→are implementation decisions finalized at T06. Only the behavioral contract\n   843→above is fixed by this specification.\n   844→\n   845→**SC-006: sprint shadow mode non-interference**\n   846→\n   847→When the wiring gate executes in shadow mode within a sprint run, the following\n   848→must hold after gate execution regardless of gate outcome:\n   849→- Task status fields (state, assignee, priority) in the sprint manifest are\n   850→  unchanged\n   851→- No exception is propagated to the sprint runner\n   852→- A `logger.info(...)` or equivalent trace is emitted with finding count\n   853→\n   854→### 9.3 Test Infrastructure\n   855→\n   856→**Fixture directory**: `tests/audit/fixtures/` (existing in file manifest)\n   857→**Size budget**: 50–80 LOC total (unchanged)\n   858→**Coverage target**: ≥ 90% line coverage on `src/superclaude/cli/audit/wiring_gate.py`\n   859→\n   860→All WiringFinding `finding_type` values (`\"unwired_callable\"`, `\"orphan_module\"`,\n   861→`\"unwired_registry\"`) must appear in at least one test assertion.\n   862→Gate exit paths (pass and fail) must each appear in at least one test assertion.\n   863→\n   864→---\n   865→\n   866→## 10. Success Criteria\n   867→\n   868→| SC | Description | Verification |\n   869→|----|-------------|-------------|\n   870→| SC-001 | Wiring gate detects `Optional[Callable] = None` never provided at call site | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_callable_basic` |\n   871→| SC-002 | Wiring gate detects orphan modules in `steps/` directories | Unit test: `test_detect_orphan_module` |\n   872→| SC-003 | Wiring gate detects unresolvable registry entries | Unit test: `test_detect_unwired_registry` |\n   873→| SC-004 | Report conforms to `GateCriteria` validation pattern | Unit test: `test_gate_passes_clean_report` |\n   874→| SC-005 | `gate_passed()` evaluates `WIRING_GATE` without modification | Integration test: `test_cli_portify_fixture` |\n   875→| SC-006 | Shadow mode logs findings without affecting task status | Integration test in sprint context |\n   876→| SC-007 | Whitelist mechanism excludes intentional optionals and records suppression count | Unit test: whitelist positive case (per Section 9.1 — whitelist test); AND `emit_report()` frontmatter includes `whitelist_entries_applied: 1` |\n   877→| SC-008 | Deviation count reconciliation catches body/frontmatter mismatch | Unit test: `test_deviation_count_reconciliation` |\n   878→| SC-009 | Analysis completes in < 5s for packages up to 50 files | Performance benchmark |\n   879→| SC-010 | Retrospective: would catch the cli-portify executor no-op bug | Run against actual `cli_portify/` directory |\n   880→| SC-011 | `provider_dir_names` pre-activation validation emits `WARN: zero-findings-on-first-run` when zero provider dirs match | Integration: shadow run against target with no matching provider dirs emits warning and halts baseline collection |\n   881→\n   882→---\n   883→\n   884→## 11. Dependency Map\n   885→\n   886→```\n   887→                  EXISTING (no changes)\n   888→                  =====================\n   889→                  pipeline/models.py\n   890→                    GateCriteria\n   891→                    SemanticCheck\n   892→                         |\n   893→                  pipeline/gates.py\n   894→                    gate_passed()\n   895→                         |\n   896→                  pipeline/trailing_gate.py\n   897→                    resolve_gate_mode()\n   898→                    TrailingGateRunner\n   899→\n   900→                  NEW\n   901→                  ===\n   902→                  audit/wiring_gate.py -------> pipeline/models.py (import)\n   903→                    |                                   |\n   904→                    v                                   v\n   905→                  audit/wiring_config.py        pipeline/gates.py (consumed by)\n   906→                    |\n   907→                    v\n   908→                  sprint/executor.py (MODIFY) -> audit/wiring_gate.py (import)\n   909→                  sprint/config.py (MODIFY)\n   910→                  roadmap/gates.py (MODIFY) -- deviation count recon only\n   911→```\n   912→\n   913→**Zero changes to existing gate infrastructure.** The wiring gate is a new consumer\n   914→of the existing `GateCriteria`/`SemanticCheck`/`gate_passed()` pattern.\n   915→\n   916→---\n   917→\n   918→## 12. Tasklist Index (for sprint execution)\n   919→\n   920→| Task | Description | Deliverables | Deps |\n   921→|------|-------------|-------------|------|\n   922→| T01 | Data models (`WiringFinding`, `WiringReport`, `WiringConfig`) | `wiring_gate.py` (partial), `wiring_config.py` | -- |\n   923→| T02 | Unwired callable analysis (`analyze_unwired_callables`) | `wiring_gate.py` (partial) | T01 |\n   924→| T03 | Orphan module analysis (`analyze_orphan_modules`) | `wiring_gate.py` (partial) | T01 |\n   925→| T04 | Unwired registry analysis (`analyze_unwired_registries`) | `wiring_gate.py` (partial) | T01 |\n   926→| T05 | Report emitter and `WIRING_GATE` constant | `wiring_gate.py` (complete) | T01 |\n   927→| T06 | Unit tests for T02-T04 + test fixtures | `tests/audit/test_wiring_gate.py` (minimum 14 unit tests per Section 9.1), `tests/audit/fixtures/` (SC-010 fixture structure per Section 9.2 behavioral contract) | T02, T03, T04 |\n   928→| T07 | Sprint integration (shadow mode hook) | `sprint/executor.py` (modify), `sprint/config.py` (modify) | T05 |\n   929→| T08 | Deviation count reconciliation | `roadmap/gates.py` (modify) | -- |\n   930→| T09 | Unit tests for T08 | `tests/audit/test_deviation_recon.py` | T08 |\n   931→| T10 | Integration test: cli-portify fixture | `tests/audit/test_wiring_integration.py` | T06, T07 |\n   932→| T11 | Retrospective: run against actual `cli_portify/` | Validation report | T10 |\n   933→\n   934→**Critical path**: T01 -> T02/T03/T04 (parallel) -> T05 -> T06 -> T07 -> T10 -> T11\n   935→\n   936→**Parallel track**: T08 -> T09 (independent of T01-T07)\n   937→\n   938→---\n   939→\n   940→## Appendix A: Forensic Report Cross-Reference\n   941→\n   942→| Forensic Finding | Section | Addressed By |\n   943→|-----------------|---------|-------------|\n   944→| `step_runner=None` no-op default | Section 1, Defect 1 | T02: unwired callable analysis |\n   945→| Steps exist but never imported | Section 1, orphaned step implementations | T03: orphan module analysis |\n   946→| `STEP_REGISTRY` is metadata-only, no function refs | Section 4 | T04: unwired registry analysis |\n   947→| Link 3 does not exist | Section 5 | T05+T07: gate definition + sprint integration |\n   948→| Gate infrastructure validates documents, not code | Section 7 | Entire release scope |\n   949→| \"Defined but not wired\" recurring pattern | Section 9, systemic | T02+T03+T04: three detection mechanisms |\n   950→| LLM fidelity report body/frontmatter inconsistency | Section 5, Appendix B | T08: deviation count reconciliation |\n   951→\n   952→## Appendix B: Naming Convention Reference\n   953→\n   954→The analysis functions use the following naming conventions to identify targets:\n   955→\n   956→| Convention | Pattern | Used By |\n   957→|------------|---------|---------|\n   958→| Injectable callable | `Optional[Callable]`, `Callable \\| None` with `= None` | T02 |\n   959→| Provider directory | `steps/`, `handlers/`, `validators/`, `checks/` | T03 |\n   960→| Dispatch registry | `*_REGISTRY`, `*_DISPATCH`, `*_RUNNERS`, `*_HANDLERS` | T04 |\n   961→| Export function | Top-level `def` not prefixed with `_` | T03 |\n   962→| Excluded file | `__init__.py`, `conftest.py`, `test_*.py` | T03 |\n   963→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"uuid":"6229cdaa-41c2-4314-971a-69cddecc635e","timestamp":"2026-03-17T18:47:35.563Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a7ed239c-6892-4726-9fa3-bf21fc31bd82","userType":"external","cwd":"/config/workspace/IronClaude","sessionId":"caf57f20-b6f0-47d7-a404-b3840c9c44e5","version":"2.1.77","gitBranch":"v3.0-AuditGates","slug":"bright-juggling-reef"}
